Martin,



Several recent topics, such as modularity, involve &quot;costs&quot;.  From a
category-theoretic or graph-theoretic context, costs usually involve a
mathematical analog to energy (or a related concept like information or
entropy) - how much energy (longer term) does it cost to: 1) generate a
non-regular, novel pattern vs. a regular pattern, 2) how much energy does it
take to project another dimension (spinor or tensor projection, for
example), etc.  There is a cost, and there is a value associated with that
cost (see: simulated annealing in graphs).  For example, the energy cost of
a human brain is substantial compared with the other organ functions.  In a
human, the value provided is worth that cost, and obviously there may be a
differentiation between physical symmetry and functional symmetry.



There are various bifurcation types and points - opportunities for the
energy costs to go up, or go down.  Various symmetries are attractive
because they require less energy (of course there exist repulsive symmetries
as well, i.e. gradient descent).  In the same way that a h-CPPN can encode
grayscale values, it can encode topological features based upon the
alternative energy / value structures (in another domain, see Agung
Budiyono&#39;s &quot;system imaginability&quot;)
http://128.84.158.119/abs/quant-ph/0512235v1 .



Directly to your point - start with a point in an appropriate context of
n-degrees of freedom.  Expand in the directions encoded in the genome that
provide the greatest value with the lowest amount of energy (see similarity
with ontogeny).



Ken Lloyd



