&gt; &gt; That certainly makes sense. It raises the question of how bilateral
symmetry arose in biological organisms.

I have no link to literature or any kind of evidence, but with regard to
this paper I was wondering what kind of creatures would emerge if you would
start with an organism that has spherical symmetry (as far as you can
represent spherical symmetry with voxels ;)) encoded through a CPPN. This
ancestor organism would be something like a unicellular organism in nature.
Starting with a CPPN of such an organism would mean that radial and
bilateral symmetry is in actual fact a departure from spherical symmetry.
And I suspect that from this starting position bilateral symmetry should be
easier to reach (and it is maybe biologically more plausible!?).

@Jeff: can you try that for us? :-)

&gt;From this perspective, complexification (or diversification) would mean
breaking the symmetry rather than approaching it, which seems to me more
natural. But as I said, I am not familiar with the literature in this area.

Best,
Martin



